[[File:A.Vesnin 5x5=25 catalog cover 1921.jpg|right|thumb|Cover art of 5x5=25 catalogue by [[Alexander Vesnin]]]] __NOTOC__ '''5x5=25''' was a two-part [[abstract art]] exhibition held in September–October 1921 in [[Moscow]]. The five artists whose work was shown were [[Aleksandra Ekster]], [[Lyubov Popova]], [[Alexander Rodchenko]], [[Varvara Stepanova]] and [[Alexander Vesnin]]. They presented highly abstracted, geometric work that rejected [[expressionist]] forms of painting common before the [[World War I]] and pretended to be the "end" or "death" of art.
Rodchenko presented three canvases of a single colour (red, yellow and blue). He saw that his formal research into [[Constructivism (art)|Constructivism]] had reached completion at this point, and claimed that he had demonstrated the "end of painting".<ref name="artdaily">[http://www.artdaily.org/section/news/index.asp?int_sec=11&int_new=26647&int_modo=1 Art Daily article on Rodchenko and his role in Constructivism]</ref> The exhibition has been considered an anti-painting manifesto.<ref name="artprof">[http://www.artprofessor.com/artists/alexander-rodchenko.php Art Professor article on Alexander Rodchenko]</ref><ref name=AA/>
Lyubov Popova showed canvasses almost bare, puzzling viewers and provoking hail from the critics. Her "flight from painting" influenced [[Wassily Kandinsky]], [[Mark Rothko]] and [[Ad Reinhardt]].<ref name=AA>{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/news/drawing-a-blank-russian-constructivist-makes-late-tate-debut-1516801.html | title=Drawing a blank: Russian constructivist makes late Tate debut | publisher=[[The Independent]] | author=Arifa Akbar | accessdate=2009-06-25 | location=London | date=January 27, 2009}}</ref> Popova herself did not regard her works as "the end"; on the contrary, she wrote, "all pieces presented here should be regarded as merely preparations for concrete construction".<ref>Gleason, Kenez, Stites, pp. 208-209.</ref>
Alexander Vesnin presented five<ref name=KM92>Khan-Magomedov, p. 92.</ref> abstract [[cubism|cubist]] canvases that appear pure abstractions but were, in fact, ultimate decomposition of human figures.<ref name=KM92/> Vesnin's catalogue cover, in particular, is typical of his book and advertising art of the period: numbers in two "lines" (5x5 and 25) are offset against the baseline, but this irregularity is "disguised" by angled lines dissecting the space.<ref name=KM93>Khan-Magomedov, p. 93.</ref>
Catalogues of the exhibition were hand-drawn by the artists and contained original artwork that has never been displayed publicly. At least ten unique albums survive in Russia to date.<ref name=KM92/> The 1921 show was reconstructed in 2009 in London's [[Tate|Tate Gallery]]. Modern critics remain divided over the question of whether "death of painting" was a genuine statement of modern art or, indeed, it was a dead end with no future.<ref name=AA/>
