'''Waste No Food''' is a [non-profit organization] that provides a web-based [[food rescue]] "marketplace" allowing excess food to be donated from the food service industry to qualified charities that work with the needy. It facilitates the donation of [[food waste]] from farms, restaurants and grocery stores to charities that can use it. Recipient charities are vetted by InnVision.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abclocal.go.com/kgo/story?section=news/local&id=8325617|title=Boy wants people to pass extra food to hungry|date=August 24, 2011|work=KGO-TV|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>
The nonprofit was founded by Kiran Sridhar, then a 12-year-old 7th grader at a Bay Area school, as a way to improve the distribution of food and reduce waste. Sridhar, now a sophomore at Stanford University, still heads the organization.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wastenofood.org/who-we-are|title=Who We Are|work=Waste No Food website|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> Waste No Food was initially focused in the [[Silicon Valley]] area and has been expanded to [[San Francisco]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2012/04/01/bay-area-teen-takes-innovative-approach-to-helping-the-hungry/|title=Bay Area Teen Takes Innovative Approach To Helping The Hungry|last=Sovern|first=Doug|date=April 1, 2012|work=CBS San Francisco|accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>
